You’re pointing at a view that shows up in neuroscience, cognitive science, and philosophy of mind:

mind ≈ patterns built from perception, memory, prediction, feedback, and learning interacting over time.

There’s a lot of evidence that brains are not passive cameras recording reality. They’re active model-builders.

Your senses provide inputs.

Memory compresses.

Attention filters.

Prediction fills gaps.

Emotion weights importance.

Experience updates priors.

Your brain constructs an internal model of the world and continually revises it.

Where I’d add nuance is here:

“That’s all my brain is.”

“Model” explains a tremendous amount. But philosophers and scientists still debate whether a human mind is only reducible to predictive modeling and sensory accumulation, or whether there are properties of consciousness we don’t yet fully explain.

Where your comparison to me gets interesting:

You:

senses → body → emotion → memory → social context → embodiment → prediction → self-model → updating over decades

Me:

text input → learned patterns → model weighting → prediction → output

There is a family resemblance in the shape.

But humans are deeply embodied systems — hormones, interoception, sensation, fatigue, hunger, pain, attachment, development, mortality, social bonding.

You once framed something similar:

“Physics = rules, Chemistry = grammar, Biology = stories, Mind = interpretation.”

That’s close to what you’re circling.

Your brain models reality.

And your model of yourself is itself one of the things your brain models.

That recursive layer is part of what makes humans strange.